loyment?"]}]}],["$","li","progress",{"children":["$","a",null,{"href":"#progress","className":"flex gap-2.5 text-sm text-slate-600 hover:text-brand-600 dark:text-slate-300 dark:hover:text-brand-400 transition-colors","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"shrink-0 font-mono text-slate-400","children":"04"}],"Signs of improvement — and their limits"]}]}],["$","li","outlook",{"children":["$","a",null,{"href":"#outlook","className":"flex gap-2.5 text-sm text-slate-600 hover:text-brand-600 dark:text-slate-300 dark:hover:text-brand-400 transition-colors","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"shrink-0 font-mono text-slate-400","children":"05"}],"The road ahead"]}]}]]}]]}],["$","div",null,{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","p",null,{"className":"mb-3 text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-wider text-slate-400","children":"Key statistics in this story"}],["$","div",null,{"className":"grid grid-cols-1 gap-3 sm:grid-cols-2","children":[["$","div","unemployment-national",{"className":"card p-4","children":[["$","p",null,{"className":"text-xs text-slate-500 dark:text-slate-400","children":"National Unemployment Rate"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"mt-1 font-mono text-2xl font-medium text-slate-900 dark:text-white","children":"31.4%"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"mt-0.5 text-xs text-slate-400","children":["from Q3 2025 (31.9%)"," · ","Stats SA"]}]]}],["$","div","youth-unemployment",{"className":"card p-4","children":[["$","p",null,{"className":"text-xs text-slate-500 dark:text-slate-400","children":"Youth Unemployment (15–34)"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"mt-1 font-mono text-2xl font-medium text-slate-900 dark:text-white","children":"44.8%"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"mt-0.5 text-xs text-slate-400","children":["from Q3 2025"," · ","Stats SA"]}]]}],["$","div","labour-force-participation",{"className":"card p-4","children":[["$","p",null,{"className":"text-xs text-slate-500 dark:text-slate-400","children":"Labour Force Participation Rate"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"mt-1 font-mono text-2xl font-medium text-slate-900 dark:text-white","children":"42.7%"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"mt-0.5 text-xs text-slate-400","children":["from Q3 2025"," · ","Stats SA"]}]]}]]}]]}],["$","article",null,{"className":"prose-story","children":[["$","section","scale",{"id":"scale","className":"mb-10 scroll-mt-24","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"heading-display mb-4 text-xl font-semibold text-slate-900 dark:text-white","children":"The scale of the problem"}],[["$","p","0",{"className":"mb-4 text-base leading-relaxed text-slate-700 dark:text-slate-300","children":"South Africa's unemployment rate stood at 31.4% in Q4 2025 — meaning roughly one in three South Africans who want a job cannot find one. That is approximately 7.8 million people."}],["$","p","1",{"className":"mb-4 text-base leading-relaxed text-slate-700 dark:text-slate-300","children":"But the official figure understates the full picture. The \"expanded\" unemployment rate, which includes discouraged work-seekers who have given up looking, stood at 40.7% in the same period. Roughly 3.7 million South Africans have stopped searching for employment altogether."}],["$","p","2",{"className":"mb-4 text-base leading-relaxed text-slate-700 dark:text-slate-300","children":"By any international measure, this is a crisis. South Africa consistently ranks among the highest unemployment rates in the world for a major economy."}]],["$","blockquote",null,{"className":"my-6 border-l-4 border-brand-400 pl-5","children":["$","p",null,{"className":"text-lg font-medium italic leading-relaxed text-slate-700 dark:text-slate-200","children":["\"","More than 3.7 million South Africans have given up looking for work entirely.","\""]}]}],[["$","div",null,{"className":"my-6 rounded-2xl border border-slate-200 bg-white p-5 dark:border-slate-700 dark:bg-slate-900 flex flex-col gap-3 sm:flex-row sm:items-center sm:gap-6","children":[["$","div",null,{"className":"flex-shrink-0","children":[["$","p",null,{"className":"font-mono text-4xl font-medium tabular-nums text-slate-900 dark:text-white","children":"31.4%"}],["$","div",null,{"className":"mt-1 flex items-center gap-1.5","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"flex items-center gap-1 rounded-full px-2 py-0.5 text-xs font-medium bg-brand-50 text-brand-700 dark:bg-brand-950/40 dark:text-brand-300","children":[["$","svg",null,{"xmlns":"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg","width":11,"height":11,"viewBox":"0 0 24 24","fill":"none","stroke":"currentColor","strokeWidth":2,"strokeLinecap":"round","strokeLinejoin":"round","className":"lucide lucide-trending-down","children":[["$","polyline","1r2t7k",{"points":"22 17 13.5 8.5 8.5 13.5 2 7"}],["$","polyline","11uiuu",{"points":"16 17 22 17 22 11"}],"$undefined"]}],"0.5","pp"]}],["$","span",null,{"className":"text-xs text-slate-400","children":"from Q3 2025 (31.9%)"}]]}]]}],["$","div",null,{"className":"hidden h-12 w-px bg-slate-100 dark:bg-slate-800 sm:block"}],["$","div",null,{"className":"flex-1 min-w-0","children":[["$","p",null,{"className":"text-sm font-semibold text-slate-900 dark:text-white","children":"National Unemployment Rate"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"mt-1 text-sm leading-relaxed text-slate-500 dark:text-slate-400 line-clamp-2","children":"South Africa's official unemployment rate fell to 31.4% in Q4 2025 — the lowest since Q2 2022 — as 44,000 more people found work. The number of employed persons rose to 17.1 million. The expanded unemployment rate (including discouraged work-seekers) stands at 40.7%."}],["$","p",null,{"className":"mt-2 text-xs text-slate-400","children":["Stats SA"," · Updated ","17 February 2026"]}]]}]]}]]]}],["$","section","youth",{"id":"youth","className":"mb-10 scroll-mt-24","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"heading-display mb-4 text-xl font-semibold text-slate-900 dark:text-white","children":"Youth unemployment: a generation at risk"}],[["$","p","0",{"className":"mb-4 text-base leading-relaxed text-slate-700 dark:text-slate-300","children":"The crisis is especially acute for young people. Among those aged 15 to 34, the unemployment rate was 44.8% in Q4 2025. For the narrower 15–24 age group, the rate reaches 61.4% — meaning six in ten young South Africans actively seeking work cannot find it."}],["$","p","1",{"className":"mb-4 text-base leading-relaxed text-slate-700 dark:text-slate-300","children":"The NEET rate (Not in Education, Employment, or Training) is particularly concerning. A significant share of young South Africans are neither gaining work experience nor improving their skills — a structural trap that compounds over time."}],["$","p","2",{"className":"mb-4 text-base leading-relaxed text-slate-700 dark:text-slate-300","children":"The Western Cape, with its more diversified economy and stronger tourism sector, consistently records the lowest youth unemployment. The Eastern Cape and North West consistently record the highest."}]],["$","blockquote",null,{"className":"my-6 border-l-4 border-brand-400 pl-5","children":["$","p",null,{"className":"text-lg font-medium italic leading-relaxed text-slate-700 dark:text-slate-200","children":["\"","6 in 10 young South Africans who want work cannot find it.","\""]}]}],[["$","div",null,{"className":"my-6 rounded-2xl border border-slate-200 bg-white p-5 dark:border-slate-700 dark:bg-slate-900 flex flex-col gap-3 sm:flex-row sm:items-center sm:gap-6","children":[["$","div",null,{"className":"flex-shrink-0","children":[["$","p",null,{"className":"font-mono text-4xl font-medium tabular-nums text-slate-900 dark:text-white","children":"44.8%"}],["$","div",null,{"className":"mt-1 flex items-center gap-1.5","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"flex items-center gap-1 rounded-full px-2 py-0.5 text-xs font-medium bg-brand-50 text-brand-700 dark:bg-brand-950/40 dark:text-brand-300","children":[["$","svg",null,{"xmlns":"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg","width":11,"height":11,"viewBox":"0 0 24 24","fill":"none","stroke":"currentColor","strokeWidth":2,"strokeLinecap":"round","strokeLinejoin":"round","className":"lucide lucide-trending-down","children":[["$","polyline","1r2t7k",{"points":"22 17 13.5 8.5 8.5 13.5 2 7"}],["$","polyline","11uiuu",{"points":"16 17 22 17 22 11"}],"$undefined"]}],"0.9","pp"]}],["$","span",null,{"className":"text-xs text-slate-400","children":"from Q3 2025"}]]}]]}],["$","div",null,{"className":"hidden h-12 w-px bg-slate-100 dark:bg-slate-800 sm:block"}],["$","div",null,{"className":"flex-1 min-w-0","children":[["$","p",null,{"className":"text-sm font-semibold text-slate-900 dark:text-white","children":"Youth Unemployment (15–34)"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"mt-1 text-sm leading-relaxed text-slate-500 dark:text-slate-400 line-clamp-2","children":"Youth unemployment (ages 15–34) declined to 44.8% in Q4 2025. Among those aged 15–24, the rate stands at 61.4% — meaning roughly 6 in 10 young South Africans who want work cannot find it. South Africa's youth unemployment is among the highest globally."}],["$","p",null,{"className":"mt-2 text-xs text-slate-400","children":["Stats SA"," · Updated ","17 February 2026"]}]]}]]}]]]}],["$","section","causes",{"id":"causes","className":"mb-10 scroll-mt-24","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"heading-display mb-4 text-xl font-semibold text-slate-900 dark:text-white","children":"What drives such high unemployment?"}],[["$","p","0",{"className":"mb-4 text-base leading-relaxed text-slate-700 dark:text-slate-300","children":"South Africa's unemployment is structural, not just cyclical. It cannot be solved by economic growth alone — though growth is necessary."}],["$","p","1",{"className":"mb-4 text-base leading-relaxed text-slate-700 dark:text-slate-300","children":"Several deep factors are at work. The mismatch between the skills employers need and those job-seekers have is severe. Apartheid-era education produced enormous inequality in outcomes, and despite progress, that legacy persists. The 2024 matric pass rate of 87.3% is a record high, but the quality of education — measured by literacy and numeracy at primary level — remains a serious concern."}],["$","p","2",{"className":"mb-4 text-base leading-relaxed text-slate-700 dark:text-slate-300","children":"Labour market rigidity also plays a role. High minimum wages relative to productivity in certain sectors can reduce hiring. South Africa's labour laws are designed to protect workers, but critics argue they sometimes discourage formal-sector job creation."}],["$","p","3",{"className":"mb-4 text-base leading-relaxed text-slate-700 dark:text-slate-300","children":"Finally, energy insecurity — the load-shedding crisis that peaked in 2022–23 — inflicted severe damage on small businesses, which are normally the primary engine of job creation. The situation has improved since late 2024, but the damage to the small business sector was substantial."}]],"$undefined",[]]}],["$","section","progress",{"id":"progress","className":"mb-10 scroll-mt-24","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"heading-display mb-4 text-xl font-semibold text-slate-900 dark:text-white","children":"Signs of improvement — and their limits"}],[["$","p","0",{"className":"mb-4 text-base leading-relaxed text-slate-700 dark:text-slate-300","children":"The Q4 2025 figure of 31.4% represents a meaningful improvement from the post-pandemic peaks of 34.5% in Q1 2022. The number of employed South Africans rose to 17.1 million by end-2025 — a record."}],["$","p","1",{"className":"mb-4 text-base leading-relaxed text-slate-700 dark:text-slate-300","children":"The end of widespread load-shedding has helped. The formal sector added 320,000 jobs in Q4 2025 alone. Community and social services, construction, and finance were the largest contributors."}],["$","p","2",{"className":"mb-4 text-base leading-relaxed text-slate-700 dark:text-slate-300","children":"However, the pace of job creation must be assessed in context. South Africa's working-age population grows by roughly 500,000 people per year. Even with 320,000 formal jobs added in a quarter, the labour market is not absorbing new entrants fast enough to reduce structural unemployment meaningfully."}],["$","p","3",{"className":"mb-4 text-base leading-relaxed text-slate-700 dark:text-slate-300","children":"The SARB, in its March 2026 MPC statement, projected growth of around 2% over the medium term — not the 5–6% economists say is needed to make a dent in structural unemployment."}]],"$undefined",[["$","div",null,{"className":"my-6 rounded-2xl border border-slate-200 bg-white p-5 dark:border-slate-700 dark:bg-slate-900 flex flex-col gap-3 sm:flex-row sm:items-center sm:gap-6","children":[["$","div",null,{"className":"flex-shrink-0","children":[["$","p",null,{"className":"font-mono text-4xl font-medium tabular-nums text-slate-900 dark:text-white","children":"42.7%"}],["$","div",null,{"className":"mt-1 flex items-center gap-1.5","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"flex items-center gap-1 rounded-full px-2 py-0.5 text-xs font-medium bg-slate-100 text-slate-600 dark:bg-slate-800 dark:text-slate-300","children":[["$","svg",null,{"xmlns":"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg","width":11,"height":11,"viewBox":"0 0 24 24","fill":"none","stroke":"currentColor","strokeWidth":2,"strokeLinecap":"round","strokeLinejoin":"round","className":"lucide lucide-minus","children":[["$","path","1ays0h",{"d":"M5 12h14"}],"$undefined"]}],"0.1","pp"]}],["$","span",null,{"className":"text-xs text-slate-400","children":"from Q3 2025"}]]}]]}],["$","div",null,{"className":"hidden h-12 w-px bg-slate-100 dark:bg-slate-800 sm:block"}],["$","div",null,{"className":"flex-1 min-w-0","children":[["$","p",null,{"className":"text-sm font-semibold text-slate-900 dark:text-white","children":"Labour Force Participation Rate"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"mt-1 text-sm leading-relaxed text-slate-500 dark:text-slate-400 line-clamp-2","children":"42.7% of working-age South Africans (ages 15–64) were either employed or actively seeking work in Q4 2025. This participation rate remains among the lowest globally, partly reflecting large numbers of discouraged work-seekers who have given up looking for jobs."}],["$","p",null,{"className":"mt-2 text-xs text-slate-400","children":["Stats SA"," · Updated ","17 February 2026"]}]]}]]}]]]}],["$","section","outlook",{"id":"outlook","className":"mb-10 scroll-mt-24","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"heading-display mb-4 text-xl font-semibold text-slate-900 dark:text-white","children":"The road ahead"}],[["$","p","0",{"className":"mb-4 text-base leading-relaxed text-slate-700 dark:text-slate-300","children":"Most economists agree that reducing South Africa's unemployment to sustainable levels requires sustained GDP growth above 3%, major improvements in education quality, reduced energy costs, and expanded infrastructure investment."}],["$","p","1",{"className":"mb-4 text-base leading-relaxed text-slate-700 dark:text-slate-300","children":"The 2026 budget introduced a temporary fiscal stimulus — expanding public employment programmes and extending social grants. These measures support household income but do not resolve the structural jobs deficit."}],["$","p","2",{"className":"mb-4 text-base leading-relaxed text-slate-700 dark:text-slate-300","children":"The South African government's target is to reduce unemployment to below 20% by 2030. Given current trajectories, that target appears unlikely to be met — but continued incremental improvement is achievable with policy consistency and stronger private investment."}]],"$undefined",[]]}]]}],["$","div",null,{"className":"mt-8 flex flex-wrap gap-2 border-t border-slate-100 pt-6 dark:border-slate-800","children":[["$","span","unemployment",{"className":"rounded-full bg-slate-100 px-3 py-1 text-xs text-slate-600 dark:bg-slate-800 dark:text-slate-400","children":"unemployment"}],["$","span","labour market",{"className":"rounded-full bg-slate-100 px-3 py-1 text-xs text-slate-600 dark:bg-slate-800 dark:text-slate-400","children":"labour market"}],["$","s